<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the `sys_script` (Business Rule)
    row that clears the `pending_reason` field on the `x_casemgmt_case` table
    inside the scoped application `x_casemgmt` whenever the case status
    transitions from `Pending` back to `In Progress`.

    PURPOSE (AAP Section 0.5.5 verbatim):
        "Pending -> In Progress: None; clears `pending_reason`"

    This Business Rule is the housekeeping companion to the Flow Designer
    subflow ../flows/sub_flows/validate_pending_transition.xml, which SETS
    `pending_reason` (Choice: Awaiting Info | Awaiting Third Party | Other)
    when the case transitions INTO Pending. When the case transitions OUT
    of Pending back to In Progress, the previously stored reason is no
    longer relevant - the operator (case_manager or assigned case_agent)
    has resumed active work on the case, and the reason for being Pending
    has been resolved. Leaving the field populated would be misleading on
    the form (it would imply the case is still waiting on something) and
    would skew any future analytics that group cases by pending reason.
    This rule guarantees the field is empty for any non-Pending case
    reached via the Pending -> In Progress transition path.

    BEHAVIOR:
        - Trigger          : BEFORE UPDATE only on the `x_casemgmt_case` table
        - Condition        : previous.status == 'Pending'
                             AND current.status == 'In Progress'
        - Action           : sets current.pending_reason = '' (empty string)
        - Other timing     : does NOT fire on insert, delete, or query

    NO ARKCASE SOURCE-SIDE ANALOG:
        ArkCase's case-status taxonomy did not include a discrete `Pending`
        sub-state with a typed reason code on the case row itself. The
        closest semantic ancestor in the ArkCase codebase is the
        `pendingStatus` String attribute on AcmTask
        (acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-task-plugin/src/main/java/com/
         armedia/acm/plugins/task/model/AcmTask.java), which tracked
        task-level pending sub-states as free-form strings. ArkCase's
        case-state service (acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-
         plugin/src/main/java/com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/service/
         ChangeCaseFileStateService.java) handled state changes by setting
        `retval.setStatus(newState)` on line 95 and `retval.setClosed(now)`
        on line 99 for CLOSED transitions; there was no equivalent
        side-effect for transitioning out of a pending-like state.
        The ServiceNow target therefore introduces this Business Rule as
        target-side-only behavior, supporting the AAP-defined Pending
        sub-state and its typed three-value Choice vocabulary.

    DEFENSIVE PREVIOUS-NULL GUARD:
        The `previous` GlideRecord is null in certain async/system contexts
        (scheduled jobs invoking GlideRecord.update(), some bulk import
        scenarios, server-side script paths that call
        GlideRecord.updateMultiple()). If there is no previous state, no
        transition can be detected, and the rule does nothing. The String()
        cast normalizes the GlideElement to a primitive string for safe
        === comparison; without the cast, GlideElement-vs-string equality
        can behave inconsistently across releases.

    VERBATIM CHOICE LABEL COMPARISON:
        The status comparison uses the EXACT verbatim Title Case labels
        defined in ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml:
            'Pending'      (7 chars, single word, Title Case)
            'In Progress'  (11 chars, two words with literal SPACE)
        These MUST match the choice values verbatim per AAP Section 0.5.7.
        ServiceNow Choice fields persist the LABEL string by default
        (not an integer ID), so the comparison is against the label.
        Misspellings such as 'In_Progress' (underscore), 'InProgress'
        (no space), 'in progress' (lowercase), or 'IN PROGRESS' (uppercase)
        would silently never match and the rule would never fire - a
        critical correctness concern.

    CLEAR PATTERN:
        The empty-string assignment `current.pending_reason = ''` is the
        canonical ServiceNow pattern for clearing a Choice field's value.
        Equivalent alternatives include `current.pending_reason.setNil()`
        and `current.setValue('pending_reason', null)`, but the empty
        string is the most universally recognized and works identically
        for non-mandatory Choice fields. Per
        ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_pending_reason.xml the field is
        non-mandatory (mandatory=false), so clearing it is a legitimate
        end-state - the row remains valid with an empty pending_reason
        for any non-Pending status.

    ORDERING WITHIN BEFORE-UPDATE PHASE:
        order=400 is intentionally INTERMEDIATE among the before-update
        rules in this scoped application. The full before-update
        execution order in this folder is:

            1) x_casemgmt_block_terminal_closed.xml         (order=100, FIRST)
            2) x_casemgmt_block_draft_backtransition.xml    (order=200)
            3) x_casemgmt_validate_assigned_agent_membership(order=300)
            4) x_casemgmt_clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress(order=400, THIS RULE)
            5) x_casemgmt_set_closed_date.xml               (order=500, LAST)

        Running at order=400 is critical because:
          * If x_casemgmt_block_terminal_closed (order=100) aborts the
            update because previous.status was already Closed, this rule
            MUST be skipped - we never want to clear pending_reason on a
            transition that the platform is about to reject. The platform
            short-circuits the BR pipeline on abort, so a higher order
            ensures we run only after that guard has passed.
          * If x_casemgmt_block_draft_backtransition (order=200) aborts
            the update because current.status == 'Draft', this rule MUST
            be skipped (the transition won't happen, so no field clear).
          * If x_casemgmt_validate_assigned_agent_membership (order=300)
            aborts the update because the assigned_agent is not a member
            of the assigned_group, this rule MUST be skipped.
          * After all guards pass and the platform is committed to the
            transition, this rule fires and clears the now-stale
            pending_reason. The subsequent x_casemgmt_set_closed_date
            (order=500) does its own work for Resolved -> Closed
            transitions and is independent of this rule's effect.
          * Pending -> In Progress and Resolved -> Closed are mutually
            exclusive transitions - a single update cannot be both -
            so order=400 and order=500 never operate on the same
            transition path simultaneously.

    NO TYPE-FILTER:
        The rule fires for ALL case types (General Inquiry, Complaint).
        The Pending state is shared across both case types per AAP
        Section 0.5.5, so per-type filtering would be incorrect. The
        type-specific transition gating is handled by the per-type
        Flow Designer flows (../flows/general_inquiry_state_machine.xml
        and ../flows/complaint_state_machine.xml); this housekeeping rule
        runs after the flow approves the transition and is type-agnostic.

    NO GLIDERECORD LOOKUPS:
        This BR operates EXCLUSIVELY on the platform-injected `current`
        and `previous` GlideRecord pair (the row being updated and its
        prior state). It performs zero `gs.getReference()` calls, zero
        `GlideRecord.get(sys_id)` calls, and zero `new GlideRecord()`
        instantiations. This is the simplest possible BR shape and
        guarantees no cross-record dependencies that could fail at
        Update Set re-import time.

    EMAIL-DISABLED CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):
        The script body MUST NOT call gs.eventQueue('...') for any email
        notification event since email is disabled on the PDI. This rule
        contains zero gs.eventQueue() calls, zero gs.email() calls, and
        zero gs.notificationEngine() calls. It performs only the
        empty-string assignment to pending_reason.

    SCOPED-NAMESPACE CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):
        - <collection>x_casemgmt_case</collection>     scoped table
        - <sys_scope>x_casemgmt</sys_scope>            scoped namespace
        - <sys_package>x_casemgmt</sys_package>        scoped application
        - script body references current.pending_reason (scoped field)
        - script body references previous.status        (scoped field)
        - script body references current.status         (scoped field)
        Zero global-scope writes. Zero modifications to OOB tables.

    NO-HARDCODED-SYS_ID CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):
        - <collection> resolves the case table BY NAME (x_casemgmt_case)
        - <sys_scope> resolves the scope record BY NAME (x_casemgmt)
        - <sys_package> resolves the application record BY NAME (x_casemgmt)
        - The script body performs ZERO GlideRecord lookups by sys_id
          literal; it operates only on the platform-injected `current`
          and `previous` GlideRecord pair.
        - The script body uses NO gs.getReference() calls and NO
          GlideRecord.get(sys_id) calls.
        - The <sys_id> element below is THIS record's own deterministic
          primary key (MD5 of "x_casemgmt_clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress"),
          which is permitted because the AAP "no hardcoded sys_id" rule
          applies to REFERENCE FIELDS pointing at OTHER records, not to
          a record's own primary key.

    UPDATE-SET LOAD ORDER (AAP Section 0.5.2):
        This sys_script record MUST be loaded AFTER:
            - ../tables/x_casemgmt_case.xml             (table this rule attaches to)
            - ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_status.xml  (field this rule reads via previous/current)
            - ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_pending_reason.xml (field this rule writes)
            - ../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml (scoped application)
            - ../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml           (scope record)
            - ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml     (the Pending/In Progress
                                                         choice values that this
                                                         rule's script compares
                                                         against)
            - ../choices/sys_choice_case_pending_reason.xml (the Awaiting Info /
                                                             Awaiting Third Party
                                                             / Other choice
                                                             values; not directly
                                                             referenced in the
                                                             script but together
                                                             they define the
                                                             field whose value
                                                             is being cleared)
        And BEFORE:
            - ../flows/sub_flows/validate_pending_transition.xml
              (the Flow Designer subflow that SETS pending_reason on
               In Progress -> Pending; this BR is its mirror that CLEARS
               pending_reason on Pending -> In Progress; both must exist
               for the round-trip housekeeping to function correctly)
            - ../seed-data/cases/x_casemgmt_case_demo_*.xml (synthetic
              demo cases including case_demo_04 which is in Pending status
              with a pending_reason populated; that case may be
              transitioned to In Progress during validation/demo, at
              which point this rule fires and clears the column)

    DETERMINISTIC SYS_ID:
        sys_id = MD5("x_casemgmt_clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress")
               = 0943b10691d8ae86fd3c2fd6994eb693
        32-character lowercase hex. The PDI accepts any valid 32-char hex
        sys_id; deriving from the record name guarantees idempotent
        re-import on a fresh PDI: re-importing the same Update Set
        produces the same sys_id, which collides on the existing record
        and updates it in place rather than creating a duplicate. This
        is the same convention used by the sibling Business Rules
        ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_set_opened_date.xml
        (sys_id = c56aeecd4086f111be2867faae9e55ad) and
        ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_set_closed_date.xml
        (sys_id = f6d63b3856121cac9b69215b2c46f64c).

    VALIDATION GATE MAPPING (AAP Section 0.7.3):
        - Gate 2 (Workflow): "All state transitions enforced for both case
          types - Invalid transitions return blocking error; task-closure
          check blocks Resolved transition". This rule completes the
          Pending -> In Progress transition by clearing the now-stale
          pending_reason. Per AAP Section 0.5.5: "Pending -> In Progress:
          None; clears pending_reason". Without this rule, a case that
          bounces from Pending -> In Progress -> Pending would carry
          forward the OLD pending reason from the first Pending stint;
          clearing on transition out ensures each Pending entry gets a
          fresh reason input from the validate_pending_transition subflow.
        - Gate 7 (Update Set): "Scoped app exported - Update Set loads
          without errors on a fresh PDI instance". The deterministic
          sys_id, reference-by-name pattern, and absence of any external
          lookups guarantee this rule re-imports cleanly with zero
          preview errors.

    NO PII (AAP Section 0.7.2):
        The script body, code comments, description text, and all field
        values contain zero real names, real email addresses, real phone
        numbers, real organizational identifiers, or any other personally
        identifiable information. The rule operates exclusively on
        synthetic case-status enumerations (Pending, In Progress) and
        the empty-string clear operation.
-->
<record_update table="sys_script">
    <sys_script action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <abort_action>false</abort_action>
        <access>package_private</access>
        <action_delete>false</action_delete>
        <action_insert>false</action_insert>
        <action_query>false</action_query>
        <action_update>true</action_update>
        <active>true</active>
        <add_message>false</add_message>
        <advanced>true</advanced>
        <change_fields>false</change_fields>
        <client_callable>false</client_callable>
        <collection>x_casemgmt_case</collection>
        <condition/>
        <description>Before-update on x_casemgmt_case: when previous.status == 'Pending' AND current.status == 'In Progress', clears current.pending_reason (sets it to empty string). Per AAP Section 0.5.5 (Pending-&gt;In Progress: clears pending_reason). Order=400 ensures this rule runs after the transition guards (block_terminal_closed at order=100, block_draft_backtransition at order=200, validate_assigned_agent_membership at order=300) but before set_closed_date (order=500), so it only fires after all guards have approved the transition. Companion to ../flows/sub_flows/validate_pending_transition.xml which SETS pending_reason on the In Progress-&gt;Pending transition; this rule CLEARS it on the reverse transition. Type-agnostic: fires for both General Inquiry and Complaint case types since the Pending state is shared. Defensive previous-null guard handles async/system contexts where previous can be null. Contains zero gs.eventQueue() calls per the email-disabled constraint and zero GlideRecord lookups.</description>
        <execute_function>false</execute_function>
        <filter_condition/>
        <is_rest>false</is_rest>
        <message/>
        <name>x_casemgmt_clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress</name>
        <order>400</order>
        <priority>100</priority>
        <rest_method/>
        <rest_method_text/>
        <rest_service/>
        <rest_service_text/>
        <rest_variables/>
        <role_conditions/>
        <script><![CDATA[(function executeRule(current, previous /*null when async*/) {
    // Per AAP Section 0.5.5 verbatim:
    //     "Pending -> In Progress: None; clears pending_reason"
    //
    // The pending_reason field is SET by the Flow Designer subflow
    // ../flows/sub_flows/validate_pending_transition.xml when the case
    // transitions INTO Pending. When the case transitions OUT of Pending
    // back to In Progress, the previously stored reason is no longer
    // relevant and would be misleading on the form. This rule guarantees
    // the field is empty for any non-Pending case reached via the
    // Pending -> In Progress transition path.
    //
    // This BR has no ArkCase source-side analog. ArkCase did not have
    // a discrete Pending sub-state with a typed reason code; this is
    // target-side-only behavior introduced by the AAP design.
    //
    // Order=400 ensures this rule runs AFTER all transition guards
    // (block_terminal_closed at order=100, block_draft_backtransition at
    // order=200, validate_assigned_agent_membership at order=300) have
    // approved the transition, and BEFORE set_closed_date (order=500)
    // which handles the Resolved -> Closed side-effect. If any earlier
    // guard aborts the action, this rule is skipped (the platform
    // short-circuits the BR pipeline on abort) - which is correct,
    // because we never want to clear pending_reason on a transition
    // that's about to be rejected.
    //
    // Defensive previous-null guard: the `previous` GlideRecord is null
    // in certain async/system contexts. If there is no previous state,
    // no transition can be detected, and the rule does nothing. The
    // String() cast normalizes the GlideElement to a primitive string
    // for safe === comparison; without the cast, GlideElement-vs-string
    // equality can behave inconsistently across releases.
    var prevStatus = previous ? String(previous.status) : '';
    var newStatus = String(current.status);

    // Verbatim Title Case status values per AAP Section 0.5.7 and the
    // sibling choice list ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml. The
    // labels ARE the stored values - ServiceNow Choice fields persist
    // the LABEL string by default, not an integer ID. Note 'In Progress'
    // contains a literal SPACE in the middle (NOT 'In_Progress', NOT
    // 'InProgress', NOT 'in progress'). Misspelled variants would
    // silently never match and the rule would never fire - a critical
    // correctness concern that is encoded by these exact string literals.
    if (prevStatus === 'Pending' && newStatus === 'In Progress') {
        // The empty-string assignment is the canonical ServiceNow pattern
        // for clearing a Choice field's value. Per
        // ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_pending_reason.xml the field is
        // non-mandatory (mandatory=false), so clearing it is a legitimate
        // end-state - the row remains valid with an empty pending_reason
        // for any non-Pending status. The next time the case transitions
        // to Pending, the validate_pending_transition subflow will prompt
        // for a fresh reason and populate the field again.
        current.pending_reason = '';
    }
})(current, previous);
]]></script>
        <sys_class_name>sys_script</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
        <sys_domain>global</sys_domain>
        <sys_domain_path>/</sys_domain_path>
        <sys_id>0943b10691d8ae86fd3c2fd6994eb693</sys_id>
        <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
        <sys_name>x_casemgmt_clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress</sys_name>
        <sys_overrides/>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_casemgmt">x_casemgmt</sys_package>
        <sys_policy/>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_casemgmt</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_script_x_casemgmt_clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress</sys_update_name>
        <sys_updated_by>admin</sys_updated_by>
        <sys_updated_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_updated_on>
        <template/>
        <when>before</when>
    </sys_script>
</record_update>
